::section{#introduction}
::meta
type: introduction
summary: "Background on long-beaked common dolphin taxonomy, acoustic communication in dolphins, and motivation for the first whistle characterization study in the Gulf of California"
::

# Introduction

In the Mexican Pacific, two subspecies of common dolphins are recognized: the
short-beaked common dolphin (*Delphinus delphis delphis*) with a cosmopolitan
distribution, and the long-beaked common dolphin (*Delphinus delphis bairdii*)
with a distribution limited to the Eastern North Pacific (ENP) Ocean
@cite{braulik2021}, including the Gulf of California @cite{urban2005}. The
taxonomy of the common dolphin (*Delphinus* sp.) has been historically troubled.
The Committee of Taxonomy of the Society for Marine Mammalogy considers
provisionally the long-beaked common dolphins distributed in the ENP as a
subspecies *D. delphis bairdii*.

Dolphins live in fission–fusion societies and use whistles to communicate during
social interactions. Whistles can vary in frequency, typically between 1 and
35 kHz. Whistle parameters of dolphins show intra- and interspecific differences
and can be used to classify and distinguish species and populations. While studies
investigating the whistle repertoire of short-beaked common dolphins are relatively
abundant, only a few have focused on the acoustics of long-beaked common dolphins
@cite{oswald2007}, none of which were conducted in the Gulf of California.

Here we present the first whistle characterization of long-beaked common dolphins
from the Gulf of California. The aim of this study is to describe frequencies,
duration, and modulation parameters of the whistles of long-beaked common dolphins
encountered in La Paz Bay, and to compare our results with a different population
inhabiting the Eastern Pacific Ocean @cite{oswald2007}.

::endsection


::section{#methods}
::meta
type: methods
summary: "Acoustic data collection in La Paz Bay (November 2020–September 2021), whistle selection and parameter extraction using Raven Pro and Luscinia, and statistical analysis via PERMANOVA and Wilcoxon tests"
::

# Materials & Methods

Data were collected in La Paz Bay, Gulf of California, Mexico, between November
2020 and September 2021. Surveys were conducted in daylight hours during calm sea
conditions (Beaufort scale ≤ 2), with a motorized research vessel (7.3 m long,
75 HP). Groups of long-beaked common dolphins were recorded with the engine off,
using a Reson TC4013.1 omnidirectional hydrophone (sensitivity −211 dB Rms ±
3 dB re 1 V/µPa, 1 Hz to 170 kHz) connected to a preamplifier Reson VP2000
Voltage EC6081 (50 dB gain, 500 Hz high-pass filter, 50 kHz low-pass filter). A
Marantz PMD661 (24-bits WAV, sampling rate 96 kHz) was used for recording.

For each recording session the predominant behavior of the group (displayed by
more than 50% of the dolphins) was recorded using continuous scan sampling method
@cite{altmann1974}. The behavior was categorized into five mutually exclusive
behavioral state categories based on dolphin ethograms. The study was fully
observational and no ethical permit was required.

A total of 270 good quality whistles (non-overlapped and clearly visible in the
spectrogram) were selected in **Raven Pro** (version 1.5, Cornell University,
Laboratory of Ornithology). Whistle frequencies and duration were then extracted
using **Luscinia** software (version 2.16.10.29.01) @cite{lachlan2007}. In
addition, the number of steps, inflection points, and contour type were visually
determined for each whistle.

- A **step** was defined as a period of constant frequency between two periods of
  the same frequency modulation.
- An **inflection point** was defined as a shift from falling to rising (or rising
  to falling) contour slope.
- Each whistle contour was classified into one of six categories @cite{ansmann2007}:
  upsweep, downsweep, convex, concave, constant frequency, and sine.

## Statistical Analysis

A chi-squared test was used to investigate the relative frequency of occurrence
of the six contour forms. Due to the non-normal distribution of whistle parameters
(Shapiro–Wilks, *p* < 0.05), non-parametric tests were used for all further
analyses.

**PERMANOVA** (Permutational Multivariate Analysis of Variance) was conducted to
test whether whistle parameters varied among dolphin groups. Variables were
transformed to $y = \ln(y+1)$ to reduce scale differences. *P* values were
calculated based on Euclidean distances using 999 permutations. Multilevel pairwise
post hoc tests with Bonferroni adjustment were performed to calculate differences
between group pairs.

A **one-sample Wilcoxon test** was used to compare the whistle parameters of
long-beaked common dolphins from the present study with those recorded in the
Eastern Pacific Ocean by @cite{oswald2007}.

Statistical tests were performed in R software (version 4.2.1) with RStudio
interface (version 2022.12.0).

## Recording Effort

::chart{#tbl-recording-effort}
::title Recording effort per dolphin group
::interpretation
Five groups of long-beaked common dolphins were recorded across five field
sessions between November 2020 and September 2021, totalling 1 hour and 34
minutes of recording. Group sizes ranged from 80 to 300 individuals. Group V,
recorded in September 2021, contributed the largest share of whistles (213 out
of 270, approximately 79%), owing to both the greatest recording effort (38 min
across 5 recordings) and a group size of 140 dolphins. Groups III and IV were
recorded on the same date (25 April 2021) but represent distinct encounters.
Group IV yielded only 3 whistles, the smallest contribution in the dataset,
possibly reflecting the small recording effort (10 min) and a group size of
80 individuals. No other dolphin species were present during any recording
session, ensuring species-specific attribution of all selected whistles.
::
| Dolphin group | Date (dd/mm/yyyy) | No. recordings | Recording effort (min) | Group size | No. whistles |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| I   | 18/11/2020 | 2 | 20 | 150 | 30  |
| II  | 09/12/2020 | 2 | 16 | 250 | 14  |
| III | 25/04/2021 | 1 | 10 | 300 | 10  |
| IV  | 25/04/2021 | 1 | 10 |  80 |  3  |
| V   | 07/09/2021 | 5 | 38 | 140 | 213 |
::endchart

::endsection


::section{#results}
::meta
type: results
summary: "Descriptive statistics of 270 whistle parameters, dominance of upsweep contour (34.44%), significant intraspecific variation among groups via PERMANOVA, and lower ending frequency, maximum frequency, duration, and inflection points compared to Eastern Pacific population"
depends_on: ["#methods"]
::

# Results

The majority of whistles (*n* = 260; 96%) were recorded while dolphins were
**traveling** (the group moving in a consistent direction with regular surfacing
intervals). Only during one encounter (*n* = 10; 4%) was the predominant behavior
**feeding** (the group pursuing prey, sometimes with deep dives).

## Whistle Contours

Out of the six whistle contour categories, the most common was **upsweep**
(*n* = 93; 34.44%), followed by concave (*n* = 78; 28.89%), downsweep (*n* = 32;
11.85%), sine (*n* = 27; 10%), convex (*n* = 20; 7.41%), and constant frequency
(*n* = 20; 7.41%) ($\chi^2$ = 114.13, df = 5, *p* < 0.001).

::chart{#fig-contour-frequency}
::title Frequency of whistle contours of the long-beaked common dolphin from the Gulf of California
::interpretation
The bar chart shows a pronounced dominance of the upsweep contour (~34%) in
the whistle repertoire of long-beaked common dolphins from La Paz Bay. Concave
whistles are the second most frequent (~29%), followed by downsweep (~12%), sine
(~10%), and convex and constant frequency in a tie at ~7% each. The distribution
is statistically non-uniform (chi-squared test, p < 0.001), indicating a
species-level preference for rising-frequency vocalizations. This upsweep dominance
is consistent with other studies on common dolphins that report upsweep accounting
for approximately 30% of whistle composition, and may be linked to the traveling
behavior observed in 96% of the recording sessions, as upsweep whistles have been
associated with social and contact functions in other delphinid species.
::
| Whistle contour    | Count (n) | Frequency (%) |
|--------------------|-----------|---------------|
| Upsweep            | 93        | 34.44         |
| Concave            | 78        | 28.89         |
| Downsweep          | 32        | 11.85         |
| Sine               | 27        | 10.00         |
| Convex             | 20        |  7.41         |
| Constant frequency | 20        |  7.41         |
::endchart

## Whistle Parameter Descriptive Statistics

Descriptive statistics and comparison with the Eastern Pacific population from
@cite{oswald2007} are shown in @ref{#tbl-whistle-params}.

::chart{#tbl-whistle-params}
::title Whistle parameters comparison between long-beaked common dolphin from the Gulf of California and the Eastern Pacific Ocean
::interpretation
The Gulf of California population (n = 270) shows a mean maximum frequency of
14.13 ± 3.71 kHz, slightly lower than the Eastern Pacific population (16.21 ±
4.94 kHz). Mean minimum frequency is nearly identical between populations
(8.44 ± 2.58 kHz vs. 8.48 ± 2.70 kHz). Mean whistle duration in the present
study is 0.44 ± 0.31 s, compared to 0.62 ± 0.34 s in Oswald et al. (2007).
The coefficient of variation (CV) for modulation parameters is notably high: >100%
for inflection points (107.61%) and even higher for steps (170.00%), reflecting
the high plasticity of dolphin whistle modulation. Frequency-related parameters
show lower CV values (25–40%), indicating comparatively greater consistency in
spectral features. Parameters marked with * showed statistically significant
differences between the two populations (One-sample Wilcoxon test, p < 0.001):
duration, maximum frequency, ending frequency, and number of inflection points.
No significant differences were found for starting frequency (p = 0.09476) and
minimum frequency (p = 0.1429).
::
::source "Oswald et al. (2007), The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America, 122:587–595"
| Whistle parameter           | Min   | Max   | Mean ± SD (present study, n=270) | CV (%)  | Mean ± SD (Oswald et al. 2007, n=174) |
|-----------------------------|-------|-------|----------------------------------|---------|----------------------------------------|
| Duration (s) *              |  0.05 |  2.17 | 0.44 ± 0.31                      |  70.45  | 0.62 ± 0.34                            |
| Maximum frequency (kHz) *   |  3.52 | 26.12 | 14.13 ± 3.71                     |  26.26  | 16.21 ± 4.94                           |
| Minimum frequency (kHz)     |  2.62 | 18.47 |  8.44 ± 2.58                     |  30.57  |  8.48 ± 2.70                           |
| Frequency range (kHz)       |  0.43 | 19.93 |  5.69 ± 3.40                     |  59.75  | —                                      |
| Starting frequency (kHz)    |  2.62 | 26.12 | 10.81 ± 4.25                     |  39.32  | 10.87 ± 4.89                           |
| Ending frequency (kHz) *    |  3.28 | 21.58 | 12.50 ± 3.78                     |  30.24  | 14.46 ± 5.12                           |
| Peak frequency (kHz)        |  3.00 | 20.55 | 10.46 ± 2.62                     |  25.05  | —                                      |
| No. of inflection points *  |  0.00 |  8.00 |  0.92 ± 0.99                     | 107.61  |  1.59 ± 3.29                           |
| No. of steps                |  0.00 |  4.00 |  0.40 ± 0.68                     | 170.00  | —                                      |
::endchart

::callout{type="note"}
Parameters marked with * showed statistically significant differences between
the Gulf of California and the Eastern Pacific populations (One-sample Wilcoxon
test, *p* < 0.001).
::endcallout

## Intraspecific Variation Among Groups

Whistle parameters showed significant differences among the five recorded groups
(F = 4.762, df = 4, *p* = 0.001). Five pairs of groups showed significant
differences in whistle parameters (see @ref{#tbl-posthoc}). Group IV showed no
significant differences with any other group, likely due to the very small number
of whistles analyzed for that group (*n* = 3).

::chart{#tbl-posthoc}
::title Multilevel post hoc pairwise tests with Bonferroni adjustment of whistle parameters between group pairs
::interpretation
Ten pairwise comparisons were conducted between the five dolphin groups. Five
pairs showed statistically significant differences after Bonferroni adjustment
(adjusted p < 0.05): I vs III, I vs V, II vs III, II vs V, and III vs V. The
II vs III comparison shows the largest effect size (R² = 0.2206), suggesting
the greatest divergence in whistle characteristics between those two groups.
Groups involving Group IV showed no significant differences with any other
group, consistent with the low whistle sample from that encounter (n = 3),
which limits statistical power. The intraspecific variation observed is
consistent with the fission-fusion social structure of this species, wherein
dolphins may adapt their whistles continuously to changing biotic and abiotic
environments.
::
| Group pairs | R²          | p     | p adjusted |
|-------------|-------------|-------|------------|
| I vs II     | 0.023576317 | 0.402 | 1.00       |
| I vs IV     | 0.057779319 | 0.112 | 1.00       |
| I vs III    | 0.143076262 | 0.001 | 0.01 *     |
| I vs V      | 0.037041288 | 0.001 | 0.01 *     |
| II vs IV    | 0.125803616 | 0.067 | 0.67       |
| II vs III   | 0.220604483 | 0.001 | 0.01 *     |
| II vs V     | 0.022609014 | 0.003 | 0.03 *     |
| IV vs III   | 0.132934612 | 0.153 | 1.00       |
| IV vs V     | 0.003419664 | 0.524 | 1.00       |
| III vs V    | 0.020883659 | 0.004 | 0.04 *     |
::endchart

## Comparison with Eastern Pacific Population

The whistles recorded in the present study showed significantly lower values than
those from @cite{oswald2007} for four parameters:

- Ending frequency (V = 8,582, *p* < 0.001)
- Maximum frequency (V = 7,786, *p* < 0.001)
- Duration (V = 7,142, *p* < 0.001)
- Number of inflection points (V = 3,378, *p* < 0.001)

No significant differences were found for starting frequency (V = 16,607,
*p* = 0.09476) or minimum frequency (V = 16,921, *p* = 0.1429).

::endsection


::section{#discussion}
::meta
type: discussion
summary: "Interpretation of whistle parameter variability, contour dominance, intraspecific group differences, and comparison with Eastern Pacific population in the context of dolphin social structure and acoustic plasticity"
depends_on: ["#results", "#methods"]
::

# Discussion

This study represents the first whistle characterization of long-beaked common
dolphin from the Gulf of California. Group sizes of the encounters ranged from
80 to 300 individuals (mean: 184 dolphins), consistent with @cite{oswald2021b},
who also reported large groups exceeding 100 individuals.

The whistles of the recorded long-beaked common dolphins spanned from 2.62 kHz
to 26.12 kHz in frequency, with durations ranging from 0.05 s to 2.17 s. The
coefficients of variation (CV) for modulation parameters (inflection points and
steps) exceeded 100%, indicating high variability in modulation patterns. This
high CV for modulation alongside low CV for frequencies and duration has been
previously reported in *Delphinus* sp. and other dolphin species, and may reflect
the influence of social or ecological factors.

## Contour Dominance

The upsweep contour was the most commonly recorded, consistent with other studies
on common dolphins where upsweep accounts for approximately 30% of whistle
composition @cite{ansmann2007} @cite{pagliani2022}. The biological meaning of
different contour types is not yet fully understood, but appears linked to
behavioral context. Upsweep whistles have been associated with social behavior in
bottlenose dolphins, while sine whistles appear more associated with traveling.
In the present study, 96% of whistles were recorded during traveling behavior,
making the upsweep dominance a potentially informative signal for future
behavioral studies in this population.

## Intraspecific Variation

The intraspecific variation among groups could be attributable to the fission–fusion
social structure of the species @cite{tyack1986}. In such fluid societies, higher
repertoire variation can be expected as dolphins adapt their acoustic output to
changing biotic and abiotic environments. Additionally, the unequal number of
whistles per group (ranging from 3 to 213) may have contributed to the observed
statistical differences; a more homogeneous sample per group would be needed to
fully assess intraspecific variation.

## Comparison with the Eastern Pacific Population

The significant differences in ending frequency, maximum frequency, duration, and
inflection points between the Gulf of California population and the Eastern Pacific
population of @cite{oswald2007} are consistent with the high plasticity of dolphin
whistles documented at both interspecific and intraspecific levels. Factors such as
geographical isolation, local ambient noise, behavioral state, group size, and
social context may all contribute to this divergence.

Characterizing whistle parameters of the long-beaked common dolphin, together with
those of the oceanic ecotype of common bottlenose dolphin in the same area
@cite{antichi2023}, will eventually support acoustic species identification using
passive acoustic monitoring. A preliminary analysis suggests the two species can
be distinguished based on the lower duration and frequency range of the long-beaked
common dolphin. Further comparative studies combining frequency parameters and
whistle contour categories will be required.

::endsection


::section{#conclusions}
::meta
type: conclusion
summary: "First whistle characterization of long-beaked common dolphins from the Gulf of California, confirming acoustic differences from the Eastern Pacific population and outlining implications for passive acoustic monitoring and conservation"
depends_on: ["#discussion"]
::

# Conclusions

This study presents the first whistle characterization of long-beaked common
dolphins from the Gulf of California, contributing to filling the knowledge gap
for this poorly studied species and providing important information for future
taxonomic studies.

Key findings are:

1. Whistles produced by long-beaked common dolphins from the Gulf of California
   differ significantly from those recorded in the Eastern Pacific Ocean in
   ending frequency, maximum frequency, duration, and number of inflection points.
2. The upsweep contour was the most common whistle type (34.44%), consistent with
   other *Delphinus* populations.
3. Modulation parameters showed high coefficients of variation (>100%), reflecting
   the acoustic plasticity typical of fission–fusion societies.
4. Significant intraspecific variation was detected among the five recorded groups.

Future comparison of whistle parameters and contours between the long-beaked common
dolphin and the oceanic ecotype of common bottlenose dolphin in the study area may
enable acoustic identification through passive acoustic monitoring, which would be
crucial for designing more focused conservation actions.

::endsection


